3️⃣ Path Cost Manipulation
Configuration (SW4)
interface f0/2
spanning-tree vlan 1 cost 100
Result
SW4 selected a different root port.
Updated behavior:
Fa0/2 → Alternate Blocking
Fa0/1 → Root Forwarding
Explanation
STP selects the root port based on lowest total path cost to the root bridge.
By increasing the cost of Fa0/2, STP recalculated and selected Fa0/1 as the new root port.
4️⃣ Port Priority Manipulation
Configuration (SW1)
interface f0/1
spanning-tree vlan 1 port-priority 240
Result
SW3 did not select a different root port.
Explanation
Port priority only influences STP when path costs are equal.
Since the root path cost remained unchanged, SW3 maintained its existing root port.
STP decision process order:
Lowest Root Bridge ID
Lowest Path Cost
Lowest Sender Bridge ID
Lowest Port Priority
Lowest Port Number
Cost is evaluated before port priority.
5️⃣ PortFast & BPDU Guard
Configuration (SW3 & SW4 F0/3)
interface f0/3
spanning-tree portfast
spanning-tree bpduguard enable
Observed Behavior (SW3)
When a BPDU was received:
%SPANTREE-2-BLOCK_BPDUGUARD
%PM-4-ERR_DISABLE
The port entered an err-disabled state.
Recovery
shutdown
no shutdown
This demonstrates:
PortFast is intended for host-facing ports.
BPDU Guard protects against accidental switch connections.
STP security features prevent Layer 2 loops.
🧠 Key Technical Takeaways
STP elects the root bridge using lowest Bridge ID.
Root primary sets priority to 24576.
Root secondary sets priority to 28672.
Path cost directly affects root port selection.
Port priority only affects tie-breaking.
PortFast bypasses listening/learning states.
BPDU Guard protects edge ports from rogue switches.
STP dynamically recalculates topology when metrics change.
